<h2>The verification standard</h2>
<p>This section describes how facts are <em>intended</em> to be verified. It is the standard the archive is built to meet. It is not a claim that every record already in the archive has passed it.</p>
<p>A fact about the world (a past or declared formulation, for example) is intended to be confirmed against two distinct-lineage sources, at least one of them primary. A fact about what a named authority states (the current regulatory position, for example) is intended to be confirmed against that authority plus an independent re-read for transcription fidelity. Anything the two passes do not agree on is withheld and routed to a human for a decision. The system never decides a genuine disagreement on its own.</p>
<p>These verification passes are carried out with the assistance of an automated system, not by two independent human reviewers. That distinction is stated plainly because the honest description of how a fact was checked is itself part of what this archive asks you to trust. A genuine disagreement is always escalated to a person, who alone resolves it.</p>

<h2>Which fields carry provenance</h2>
<p>A field is fact-bearing if and only if its schema uses the shared SourcedValue envelope. That envelope makes a source, confidence, evidence and a last-updated date mandatory on the field, so the build fails if any of them is missing. This guard enforces provenance only on fields already declared as the envelope; it cannot, by itself, catch an empirical field that was mistakenly modelled as a bare value. A separate schema-consistency check is responsible for that (DATA-09).</p>

